item.title: Aliens O.O
item.dc:creator: @ziplock ziplock
item.description:
@ziplock wrote:

[quote=“Hash1 Single, post:42, topic:428816”][quote author=ziplock link=topic=531512.msg3885612#msg3885612 date=1326411354]

Looks more like some dudes home made spy plane but I do believe in alien life. It’s impossible that out of the billions of solar systems, we are the only ones.

Sure, there’s certainly extraterrestrial life. That doesn’t mean there is extraterrestrial intelligent life. It’s not an arrogant thing with humans whatsoever, it’s simply evolutionarily “lucky” humans even came about. You can see it that from the millions of species on earth, we are the only intelligent one. Planets don’t differ from that ratio at all. There are very few planets out of the many, MANY we have found that could potentially support us. You still have the incredibly rare evolutionary chance those planets actually developed intelligent life. Cosmologically, there are incredibly low chances there is other intelligent life in this universe.

Honestly, all this shit is just wishful thinking brought on by the science fiction nutjobs of the 60s (not that I don’t love science fiction. :P)

Yes there are very few planets, if any really, that could support us. Planets are not created to fit the needs of organisms, but organisms are created to fit the needs of the planet. Intelligent life wouldn’t have to evolve just like us. Maybe on some other planet, organisms have evolved to live off other elements besides water. Still, the chances of more intelligent life to evolve is extremely slim.
[/quote]

I’m sure Earth would be two folds greater without humanity on it[/quote]

By that I did not mean that it would promote the planet any. I meant that the organism will “mold” to the planet, instead of the planet “molding” to the organism. Which is why a planet doesn’t necessarily have to contain water to sustain life.

Many people wonder if there is intelligent extraterrestrial life, and there is a good chance that there is as large as out universe is. However, that doesn’t mean they will come and greet us guns-a-blase or with open arms offering us other worldly intelligence. They could be living like many animals on earth are now, and just surviving.

@ Wet Dreamss

Travel to the past is impossible with the laws of nature. Although travel to the future is possible with high levels of gravity (look up Steven Hawking’s theory on the subject). Also, what Taharok (I probably butchered your name) was trying to explain was that if the aliens were sited by humans, or alter a single thing in the past (witch is almost unavoidable), a paradox will happen.
